definition.value: A pyrimidone that is uracil with methyl group substituents at positions 3 and 5.
A dipeptide composed of L-proline and L-hydroxyproline residues. It is a biomarker for bone collagen degradation.
An aluminium sulfate that contains no water of crystallisation.
A nucleotide residue derived from 2-methyladenosine 5'-monophosphate.
An organic sodium salt consisting of equimolar amounts of naproxen(1-) anions and sodium anions.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 2-methyladenine as the nucleobase.
A nucleotide residue derived from N(3)-methyluridine 5'-monophosphate.
Any inorganic sulfate salt resulting from the formal condensation of aluminium hydroxide with 1.5 mol eq. of sulfuric acid.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 3-methyluracil as the nucleobase.

A dicarboximide that is  thalidomide substituted at position 5 by an ethenyl group, which in turn is substituted by a feruloyl group at position 2. The compound is a hybrid based on the structures of  thalidomide and curcumin and has been found to exhibit cytotoxicity against human multiple myeloma cells.

A dicarboximide that is thalidomide substituted at position 5 by an ethenyl group, which in turn is substituted by two feruloyl groups at position 2. The compound is a hybrid based on the structures of thalidomide and curcumin and has been found to exhibit cytotoxicity against human multiple myeloma cells.
A tetrahydroxyflavone having the hydroxy groups are located at positions 3', 4', 5 and 7 as well as an additional methyl substituent at position 3.
A nucleotide residue derived from N(4)-methylcytidine 5'-monophosphate.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having N(4)-methylcytosine as the nucleobase.

A hydrate resulting from the the formal combination of anhydrous aluminium sulfate with approximately 18 mol eq. of water. The commercial product usually contains 5-10% less water than theory. It is one of the commonest hydrates of aluminium sulfate.
A hydrate resulting from the the formal combination of anhydrous aluminium sulfate with approximately 16 mol eq. of water. It is one of the commonest hydrates of aluminium sulfate.
A nucleotide residue derived from 5-carboxymethylaminomethyluridine 5'-monophosphate.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 5-carboxymethylaminouracil as the nucleobase.
A compound that causes the contraction of body tissues, typically used to reduce bleeding from minor abrasions.
A nucleotide residue derived from 5-carboxymethylaminomethyl-2'-O-methyluridine 5'-monophosphate.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is the  5-carboxymethylaminomethyl-2'-O-methyl derivative of uridine 5'-monophosphate.
A nucleotide residue derived from N(2),N(2)-dimethylguanosine 5'-monophosphate.
A nucleotide residue derived from 8-methyladenosine 5'-monophosphate.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 8-methyladenine as the nucleobase.

An aminoacridine that is acridine in which the hydrogen at position 9 is replaced by an amino group. A fluorescent dyd and topical antiseptic agent, it is used (usually as the hydrochloride salt) in eye drops for the treatment of superficial eye infections.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-isoleucine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-leucine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-lysine residues.
An anthocyanin cation that is the 3-O-beta-D-glucoside of peonidin (methylcyanidin).

A member of the class of tetrahydrothiophenes that is tetrahydrothiophene in which the sulfur has been oxidised to give the corresponding sulfone. A colourless, high-boiling (285degreeC) liquid that is miscible with both water and hydrocarbons, it is used as an industrial solvent, particularly for the purification of hydrocarbon mixtures by liquid-vapour extraction.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-phenylalanine residues.

A mannooligosaccharide derivative consisting of four D-mannose residues linked sequentially alpha(1->2), alpha(1->2) and alpha(1->3), the reducing-end residue of which is beta-linked to a 5-aminopentyl group
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-tryptophan residues.
A serine derivative that is L-serine with a methyl group replacing the hydrogen on the hydroxy side chain.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-tyrosine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-valine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-serine and L-alanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-serine and L-asparagine residues.

An oxazolidinone that is 1,3-oxazolidin-2-one substituted at position 1 by a (5-nitro-2-furyl)methylene]amino group and at position 5 by a morpholin-4-ylmethyl group. An antibacterial formerly used oraly but withdrawn due to toxicity, it is used topically (as the hydrochloride salt) for treatment of ear disorders.
A quinolone that is 4-quinolone substituted at positions 2 and 3 by hydroxy and carboxy groups respectively.
A quinolone that is 4-quinolone substituted at position 3 by a formyl group.
A dipeptide formed from L-serine and L-aspartic acid residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-serine and L-glutamine residues.
An anthocyanidin 3-O-beta-D-sambubioside having pelargonidin as the anthocyanidin component.
An anthocyanidin 3-O-beta-D-sambubioside having delphinidin as the anthocyanidin component.
An anthocyanidin 3-O-beta-D-sambubioside having cyanidin as the anthocyanidin component.
